Feeding an obese child: don't eat breakfast not and drinks for dinner
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9 per cent of schoolchildren have overweight weights and 5 per cent are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human person lives and the models around them.
On the tables of obese children, for example, carbies are 50 per cent more often than in the families of children with normal weights.
19% of obese people had french fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of the big boys, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% replied that at least once a week parents find time for the active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever Society.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 pupils from the sixth to the third have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight, or even obese, children are unable to eat properly and not enough physical exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned indicates, for example, eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case--luce--shop-dinner, which is a basic principle of good nutrition," says one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and dinner meats
Specialists draw attention to the fact that in order to have healthy development requires a few basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 per cent of students' families eat at the same time.
In most of the families, each has breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been raised is that one tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy fried fried frenchries in obese children are more often consumed.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of children questioned play sports regularly, but for parents it is only half, only 15 per cent.
Get your food ready
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food from possibilities according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from the ideal level towards a healthy diet".
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
'Most alarming is in particular a great preference for sweet lemonades,' is indicated in the results of the survey.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place just in front of the white meat.
The children did not want starchy foods at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Focus on health
The survey also showed that children are prepared to change their habits as soon as they receive ad hoc information.
"During a check-up by a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' awareness, the results of the survey have been determined to move towards a healthy diet," says the results of the survey.
The most significant was, for example, with regard to sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often ticked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main course and would reduce sweet and knedliky dishes (the Czech specialty of bread flour or potato dumpsters).
