IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York City a hundred years ago; it was originally the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - originally it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 presided over the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
The leader then cast a shadow over the founder of the firm - it was on Watson's ideas that the identity and culture of society have so far been based.
