How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotick, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A large exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In the event that the citizen Czechoslovak wishes to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he or she needed a letter of invitation, otherwise the individual journey was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered travel to the West, but it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency agreement that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not, however, redeemable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the foreign currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs were buying up and this habit has lasted until now.
The travel of the Czechs has since undergone a great revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at most, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbouring countries of the 1990s caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel by air to the west for long, which everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a boarding house.
The typical feature of a trip by Czechs was at that time to take with one's own preserved food, sausage, etc. to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech koruna, which finally allowed our tourists after decades to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average wages have increased, which has led to another important time around 1997.
Thanks to the growing demand for travel, travel agents have been beginning since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter flights which, through contracts, have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s of the last century, Czechs had visa-free routes with almost most developed countries around the world apart from the US, which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism was prepared, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic was prepared.
Since then, every year direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year.
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 kroons per person on holidays abroad including related charges. Crowns per person.
