The cheating narratives of the school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given the test responses to students in order to be seen clearly on their performance assessments.
Menrs who should teach otherwise send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
Over a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners are lying three times within the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to exclaim: 'I have had you', detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been debunked.
The liars look you in the eye.
They do not stammer, blushe or always agitate.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can uncover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the facial microexpressions, the formation of the question and the response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and still emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are adept at reading others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies 'centric about them' while women say more lies 'centric about others' - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people less often lie to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they say tend to be enormous).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if anyone is lying?
First of all, look at the normal behavior of your subject.
This is known as the "setting the reference data".
This helps to provide a baseline for measuring subsequent changes.
Look at the posture of your subject, the laughter, the voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves their feet all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see them moving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal, non-verbal deceptive behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, significantly change their posture or present relief from "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions are over.
Interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview is finished just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson slipped using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use a language that has been out of place: "I haven't had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a hard question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden tongue" in their answer to a difficult question: "Well... to say the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimisation by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
