Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to bear the brink of economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone in jeopardy.
A presidential palace statement announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he could form the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in its majority by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive assumes his job.
Monti said that he would present to the president the result of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase", said the former European Commissioner for Journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The 'frame is now well drawn,' he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, as Italy was fighting a political and financial crisis that pushed the costs of its debt to unsupported levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By pointing to the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of markets has placed the yield on Italian construction bonds at 10 years above the 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland have been saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: 'We said that we would support this government a lot'.
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Monti’s chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, to which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed Monti's technocratic majority government.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign benches has added to the pressure, observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups on Monday and youth and women's organisations.
He will finish his meeting tour on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who empowered an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italy’s debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.9 trillion, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should persist until the future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give it time to implement the reforms before putting the elections forward.
Monti said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that he should be trained only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
