The UNAM asphalt would prevent blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yields, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the reports that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand blackcurrants every rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Metropolitan Area of México, warned Rafael Herrera Nojera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous bulb was adequate, the cases could be eliminated.
During his conference A Technology Opinion on blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera suggested that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of molecules of hydrocarbons, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltene, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malhenes, which together give the pavement its viscoelastic behavior characteristic.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of nearly 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C. its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C. it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible paving stone, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small asphalt-sized and subsequently compacted stones.
Each of the little stones that forms the layer, it signaled, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating forces, the latter allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If modified asphalt were used, they would spread better, opined the chemical ingenuous.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a last layer called the tread layer, made of fine stone, that is to say, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the block that receives and distributes the forces, the tread layer also requires that the latter have an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these considerably affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil becomes wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for the latter to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that gets damaged is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programmes.
The member of the National Researcher System explained that vehicle loads are another important factor for the formation of blackcurrants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the block must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow blackcurrants to be repaired easily and without having to use high temperatures.
