Japan is back after the earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% through domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, Japan’s economy has been paralysed, still convalescent after the devastating nuclear-crisis earthquake, the worst disaster in the Japanese country since World War II.
The first estimates by the Tokyo Government have calculated the material losses at USD 300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualised rates.
The second quarter recorded - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the largest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery was partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investment by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditure from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that calls for the crisis to consolidate – or rebuild – infrastructure, use the gaps to grow zero.
Japan has woken up mainly due to changes in domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased a 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
