Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, according to Royal Society of Canada report
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health-care institutions, and doctors to work together to provide better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements for doing so.
This was one of the findings of a massive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code to permit assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient who is deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death".
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6 per cent of them die in hospital.
Overall, in the country, Quebec has the highest rate, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the report came to conclusions that contradict the position of the federal government, which had already said that they did not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all the countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on competent or unconsenting persons.
On the contrary, said yesterday in teleconference, Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, there are more cases of these spillovers precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalised.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
It should be recalled that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of older people or people with disabilities are of less value.
