The Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia and moving to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, entered into service.
It has to supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with vigour.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, last Tuesday, took part in the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte jointly turned the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe via a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Hopeonia.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, making it possible to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site has victorious airs.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
Nord Stream will make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to the West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of weakening the Europe of energy, since the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has, in just five years, managed to achieve its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily consumed by gas, whose fields are in decline.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically", confirmed François Fillon, inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the large smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in large numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-woven steel in order to protect it from ships' anchors.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
In order to build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be kidnapped or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Muller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the number of measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel turns, which nothing interrupts its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project officials gave it up, while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently sailing off their coasts.
"In the event of damage, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Muller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft operating inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 metres second, he provides precise information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate 50 years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 bars on arrival.
Five companies joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) joined, as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in the city of zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased all gas transmission capacity to the company for 20 years renewable.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Muller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy pine-planted coastline.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
