A success that made it envious: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organises the week for the employment of the disabled. "
"The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher. "
"However, there is still a lot to be done. "
It must be said that for the unemployed disabled, there are still many obstacles before they can access employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, these are all criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to work, and which "past the crux of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, the general manager of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
There remains the unsaid, the attitudes that are changing, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychological or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, dating from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We are now around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, Director General of AgeFph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The proof: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, increasing 59 000 to 46 000 structures (from 606 million to EUR 480 million).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
